article.headline: (18) WAKE FOREST 78, TEXAS TECH 73 (2OT)
article.story:
NEW YORK (Ticker) -- Friday's clash between Wake Forest and 
Texas Tech certainly did not have the feel of a consolation
game.

Justin Gray made numerous clutch shots en route to a team-high
18 points and Kyle Visser added a superb all-around effort as
18th-ranked Wake Forest outlasted Texas Tech, 78-73, in a
double-overtime thriller to win the consolation game of the 2K
Sports College Hoops Classic.

With 13.6 seconds left in regulation, Wake Forest guard Michael
Drum was fouled with a chance to put the Demon Deacons up three
points.  The walk-on starter made the first free throw but
missed the second, and Texas Tech's Jarrius Jackson made him pay
by nailing a game-tying runner with 4.9 seconds left.

Gray missed an off-balance 3-pointer at the buzzer, but he more
than made up for it in the extra sessions.

Texas Tech jumped out to an early 64-59 lead in overtime, but
Wake Forest battled back behind Gray, who nailed a 3-pointer
with one minute left to bring the Demon Deacons within 64-63.

Martin Zeno made two free throws with 16.7 seconds left to
restore a three-point lead, but Gray responded with a dramatic
game-tying 3-pointer from well beyond the arc on the right wing
to tie it at 66-66 with 3.7 seconds left.

"Sometimes I have trouble focusing when I turn the ball over,"
said Gray, who has struggled so far in the transition from
shooting guard to point guard.  "Down the stretch, coach gave me
the opportunity to make plays and I tried to will us to a win."

Drum opened the scoring in the second extra session with a
3-pointer from the left wing.  After the teams exchanged
jumpers, Drum added a pair of free throws for a 73-68 lead with
2:53 left.

The Red Raiders had a chance to slice into the deficit but
Jackson made just 2-of-4 foul shots in the final minute.  Texas
Tech's best player, Jackson finished with 27 points, but made
only 2-of-6 attempts from the line.

Gray put away the game with a tough fadeaway jumper with 23.7
seconds left that gave Wake Forest a 75-70 lead and ensured the
Demon Deacons would not lose two games in November for the
first time in school history.

"We kept fighting, we took a tough loss yesterday (against
Florida) and we knew we had to bounce back like men," Gray said.
"I'm proud of the fellas today."

Visser added 16 points, 15 rebounds and five blocks - all career
highs - for Wake Forest, which won despite shooting just 35
percent (26-of-74) from the floor.

"With him blocking shots for us, it's a big help," Gray said.
"He grabbed offensive rebounds, too.  It's a big win."
